  "prompt": "Where can I study at Stanford?",
  "response": "At Stanford University, there are many places where you can study, depending on your preferences and needs:\n\n1. **Stanford Libraries**: \n   - **Green Library**: This is the main library for humanities and social sciences and offers a variety of study spaces.\n   - **Lathrop Library**: Known for its technology resources and study spaces, including 24-hour study rooms.\n   - **Hohbach Hall**: Located within Green Library, caters to engineering, business, and other sciences.\n   - **Meyer Green**: Study and collaborative spaces.\n\n2. **Engineering Library**: Located in the Huang Engineering Center, it provides spaces for engineering students.\n\n3. **Stanford Graduate School of Business Library**: Offers resources and study spaces for business students.\n\n4. **Student Centers**:\n   - **Old Union**: Offers comfortable seating and is a popular informal study space.\n   - **Tresidder Memorial Union**: A bustling space with cafes, ideal for a more lively study atmosphere.\n\n5. **Outdoor Spaces**:\n   - **The Oval**: Offers a beautiful outdoor area for studying on nice days.\n   - **White Plaza**: Centrally located with an active atmosphere.\n  \n6. **Cafes and Dining Halls**: Many students prefer studying in cafes such as Coupa Caf\u00e9 or CoHo, or in dining halls during off-peak hours.\n\n7. **Residential Commons**: If you live on campus, you\u2019ll have access to study areas within your dorm complex.\n\n8. **Engineering Quad**: Various buildings in the quad have study spaces designed for engineering students.\n\n9. **Bechtel International Center**: Offers spaces and resources primarily for international students but is open to everyone.\n\nRemember that the availability of these places might change, and it\u2019s always a good idea to check for any restrictions or changes in hours.",
